<h1>@HI{{kenjougo}}: Humble Language</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

@include{{"honorific-humble-verbs-table.inc"}}

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{kenjougo}} is used when referring to the one's own actions or state and serves to humble
oneself to show respect to the other party.
</p>

<p>
Verbs are affected in various ways.
</p>

<h3> @HI{{o}}@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{shimasu}} </h3>

<p>
The @HI{{o}}@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{shimasu}} construction can be used for most regular @1D{{}}
and @5D{{}} verbs to produce a humble form of the verb.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{heavy}}soudesune.o@KJ{{hold}}chishimashouka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It looks heavy. Shall I carry it for you? 
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
It cannot be used with verbs whose stem is just one mora.
</p>

<h3> @HI{{go}}@Vmasustem{{}} </h3>

<p>
The @HI{{go}}@Vmasustem{{}}  construction can be used for verbs that involve @HI{{suru}} or
@HI{{kuru}}. Only those verbs which imply some connection with the listener can be used.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kyouno@KJ{{beforehand^determine}}wogo@KJ{{explanation^bright}}shimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I will explain today's schedule.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@HI{{denwashimasu}} and @HI{{yakusokushimasu}} are exceptions to the pattern that take @HI{{o}} instead of
@HI{{go}}.
</p>

<h3> Special Humble Verb Forms </h3>

<p>
The above constructions cannot be used with some verbs.
These verbs have special humble forms, as shown
in the table above.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{ashitaha darega @KJ{{hand^transmit}}ini @KJ{{come}}te kuremasuka.}}
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ga @KJ{{pay*respects}}imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: Who will come over to help me tomorrow?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: I will.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

